node.title: An anti-intensification housing media blitz
node.description: Mediawatch: Opponents of the bipartisan bill aimed at enabling housing blitzed the media over the past few weeks, but many of the reports failed to include relevant context and balancing opinion… Audio

node.title: Michigan Rolls to a Playoff Spot With Big Ten Title
node.description: The Wolverines followed up a season-defining win over Ohio State with an easy victory over Iowa to win the conference championship.

node.title: Six new COVID-19 cases reported in SA as exposure sites linked with former premier announced
node.description: Six new COVID-19 cases are reported in South Australia, including one whose source is being investigated. SA Health also lists six new exposure sites in the Adelaide CBD and Glenelg.

node.title: Ultralight plane crashes in Perth, in second such incident in under a month
node.description: An ultralight plane crashes on the outskirts of Perth, leaving two people in hospital with what are believed to be non-life-threatening injuries.

node.title: Thousands protest in Ballarat as Victoria records 980 new COVID cases and seven deaths
node.description: Dozens of businesses close as thousands of protesters descend on the regional Victorian city of Ballarat in another day of demonstrations against the state's vaccine rules and pandemic legislation.

node.title: Head in, Khawaja misses out — Australia names its XI for the first Ashes Test
node.description: Australia finalises its Test team for the opening match of the Ashes series at the Gabba, with Travis Head getting the nod ahead of Usman Khawaja to bat at number five against England.

node.title: Body of missing man Travis Davis pulled from Sunshine Coast surf
node.description: The body of missing man Travis Davis is pulled from surf on Queensland's Sunshine Coast.

node.title: 'Full steam ahead' for Cook Islands- NZ bubble reopening
node.description: Quarantine and isolation-free travel between New Zealand and the Cook Islands resumes on 14 January, despite a recent case in Rarotonga.

node.title: Was a young girl adopted from Russia capable of murder?
node.description: Saying they feared for their safety, an American couple gives up the daughter they welcomed into their family. "48 Hours" contributor Troy Roberts revisits the case that he says haunted him for years and forever changed his life.

node.title: Training for a Double Dutch Competition
node.description: Watch two teams practice for the 30th anniversary of the Double Dutch Holiday Classic at the Apollo Theater in Harlem.

node.title: The when, where and why of COVID-19 vaccines for five to 11-year-olds
node.description: When can kids get Pfizer? Is it the same vaccine adults receive? And should all kids be getting it? Here are the details of the rollout of vaccines for children aged five to 11.

node.title: One patient’s painstaking path through long Covid therapy.
node.description: By Pam Belluck

node.title: Body pulled from Sunshine Coast surf after divers search for missing man
node.description: A body is found in waters off Shelley Beach near Caloundra, almost 24 hours after a Brisbane man went missing along a treacherous stretch of beach.

node.title: Australian regulators give provisional approval to Pfizer vaccine for kids
node.description: Australia's medicines regulator has given provisional approval to the Pfizer vaccine for children aged between five and 11.

node.title: Chris Cuomo: CNN fires presenter over help he gave politician brother
node.description: US anchor Chris Cuomo has been fired by CNN for help he gave his brother, ex-New York governor Andrew Cuomo, while he was battling harassment allegations.

node.title: SH5 closed after serious crash
node.description: State Highway 5 is closed at Wairakei in the Taupō District after a serious crash near Palmer Mill Road.

node.title: Part of SH6 on West Coast closed after flooding
node.description: A section of the South Island's State Highway 6, which runs down the West Coast, has been closed due to flooding.

node.title: A woman is impaled by a corn rake, but do her fatal injuries add up to murder?
node.description: A farmer's wife is found in a shed on their Iowa farm with a corn rake lodged in her back. The rake has just four tines – so why does she have six puncture wounds?

node.title: Liz Cambage has 'zero' interest in Opals ahead of Women's World Cup
node.description: The Opals will almost certainly enter next year's Women's World Cup in Sydney without superstar Liz Cambage.

node.title: Woman rescued from roof of ute on flooded road in Western Downs
node.description: A Springvale grazier says he spotted the woman while he was using a jet ski to check on his cattle in the flood. More rain is expected in parts of southern Queensland later this week.

node.title: 6 Michigan teens charged for allegedly threatening schools
node.description: A seventh teenager was charged for allegedly possessing a weapon in a school zone.

node.title: Breakers no match for South East Melbourne Phoenix in NBL opener
node.description: An undermanned Breakers side have been put to the sword in their opening game of the NBL season.

node.title: Sydney Opera House seagull patrols a success for eateries
node.description: Dog patrols to scare away seagulls swooping on Sydney restaurant diners have been a success, with the patrol winning a repeat contract.

node.title: Sydney team unlocking more about how Omicron works
node.description: Virologist Sarah Palmer and her colleagues at Sydney's Westmead Institute virus research centre are working overtime to learn more about the Omicron variant.

node.title: Charging the parents after a US school shooting is unusual, but it has happened before
node.description: Guns used in United States school shootings have often come from the homes of young perpetrators but parents are rarely charged for the violence that occurs, experts say.

node.title: ACT records six new COVID-19 cases, confirms second Omicron infection
node.description: The ACT records six new COVID-19 cases as authorities confirm its second case of the Omicron variant. The ACT's first Omicron case has also been linked to a Sydney climbing gym.

node.title: Deputy PM says apology issued over ‘incident’ at Nationals Christmas party involving NT Senator
node.description: The office of Deputy Prime Minister Barnaby Joyce confirms an apology has been received after an incident at a Canberra pub where one witness told the ABC that Senator McMahon threw several punches towards Nationals federal director Jonathan Hawkes.

node.title: One dead and dozens burned in Indonesia eruption
node.description: One person has died and 41 have burn injuries as Mt Semuru erupts on Indonesia's Java island.

node.title: US school shooting suspect's parents deny manslaughter charges
node.description: Bail is set at $US1 million ($NZ1.4m) for the couple arrested in Detroit after failing to attend court on Friday.

node.title: What I really want for Christmas: Jackie Clark
node.description: What do people who work to improve the lives of others really want for their communities this Christmas. In the first instalment of a new RNZ series, Jackie Clark of The Aunties shares her wishlist.
